{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Robotic arms offer the opportunity of increasing stability, accuracy, and dexterity during needle positioning with fewer adjustments.",
    "Accurate placement is important to avoid loss of time, additional X-ray exposure, misdiagnosis in liver biopsy, or incomplete treatment in tumor ablation [16].",
    "In [12], the Epione (Quantum Surgical, Montpellier, France) system was used in a clinical study to perform robotic-assisted CTguided percutaneous needle insertion for hepatic thermal ablation.",
    "Other attempts for robotic CT-guided biopsies have shown that reducing the number of check scans can reduce the duration of the procedure and the radiation dose without sacrificing the accuracy of the procedure [7].Additionally, robotic arms can be teleoperated to perform surgical tasks such as needle insertion.",
    "A tele-operated X-ray-guided insertion would enable the interventional radiologist to perform the procedure without radiation exposure."
  ],
